%description:
Regression test for controller-death fallback (RFC 8231 Section 5.2 state timeout,
Workstream F4 Phase 3, RSVP-MBB mode) -- this workstream's headline behavior: a PCC whose
PCEP session to its PCE dies, and stays dead, eventually gives up waiting and falls back to
LOCAL (non-PCE) path computation for every LSP it had delegated, rather than leaving them
stuck forever waiting for a controller that never comes back.

Same ad hoc diamond + real end-to-end hosts as the sibling pcep_pcupd.test (host1 -- LSR1 ->
{LSR2 (600 kbps), LSR3 (10 Mbps)} -> LSR4 -- host4, LSR1.classifier statically FEC-binding
host4's traffic to lspid 100), PLUS a fifth router, PceRouter, hanging off LSR4 on its own
leaf link and running the ~Pce (instead of LSR4 itself, unlike pcep_pcreq.test/pcep_pcupd.test)
-- deliberately, so that killing the PCE (a ~ScenarioManager "shutdown" of PceRouter, the same
technique ldp_peer_death.test/rsvpte_mbb.test already use for a node kill/restart) can NEVER be
confused with a data-plane failure: PceRouter sits on neither the LSR2 nor the LSR3 branch, so
tunnel 1's own forwarding path (LSR1 -> LSR2/LSR3 -> LSR4 -> host4) is completely undisturbed
by PceRouter's death -- this test is about the CONTROLLER dying, not the network.
"reoptimizeInterval" is left at its default (0, off): the only thing that ever reroutes tunnel
1 in this test is the state-timeout fallback itself, not an internal reoptimization racing it.

Scenario:
  1. At t=0, tunnel 1 (lspid 100, 50 kbps, permanent, computeEro=true, computationMode="pce",
     delegate=true) is configured from the static traffic.xml, establishes over the PCE-
     computed route (~3-5s in, same PCEP-session-startup lag as pcep_pcreq.test/
     pcep_pcupd.test), and is reported to the PCE (PCRpt, PLSP-ID 1).
  2. At t=8s (well after tunnel 1 is fully up and reported), PceRouter is shut down. Its PCEP
     TCP session with LSR1's Pcc dies; since PLSP-ID 1 is still delegated at that moment, the
     Pcc starts its "stateTimeout" (configured to 5s for this test) rather than reacting
     immediately -- RFC 8231 Section 5.2 gives the PCE a real grace period to come back, and
     this test deliberately never restarts PceRouter, so that grace period is what is actually
     exercised (not an immediate reaction that would defeat the point of having a timeout at
     all).
  3. At t=13s (8s + the 5s stateTimeout), with the PCEP session still down, the Pcc tells
     ~RsvpTe to fall back to local computation for PLSP-ID 1. ~RsvpTe::revertToLocalComputation()
     immediately make-before-break re-routes it (a fresh replacement Lsp_Id, 101 -- the XML
     only ever configures lspid 100 in this test, so maxLspId is 100 going in) with its ERO
     cleared and localFallback set, forcing createIngressPSB() into its LOCAL CSPF branch
     (Ted::calculateShortestPath()) regardless of "computationMode" still being "pce" --
     nothing is ever sent to (or expected from) the PCE for this event; there is nothing left
     to send it to anyway.
  4. The replacement establishes, the classifier's FEC entry is rebound to lspid 101, and
     lspid 100 is torn down -- ordinary make-before-break cutover, just LOCAL-CSPF-driven
     this time instead of PCE-driven.

Asserted:
1. The PCEP session comes up, tunnel 1 establishes, and it is reported to the PCE (PCRpt) --
   all before PceRouter is shut down (ordering regex).
2. The state timeout is armed on session loss (NOT an immediate fallback) and expires only
   after its configured delay, at which point ~RsvpTe is told to fall back for PLSP-ID 1.
3. The fallback re-route is computed via LOCAL CSPF (the "CSPF computed ERO for session..."
   EV_DETAIL line, ~RsvpTe's own local branch), NOT via any further PCEP exchange -- no
   "PCReq sent to PCE" or "PCE computed ERO" line is ever produced for lspid 101 (structural
   %not-contains: with localFallback set, createIngressPSB() never even reaches the
   "computationMode == pce" branch for this specific replacement).
4. The cutover completes (classifier rebound from lspid 100 to 101) and traffic keeps
   flowing end to end, strongly, across the whole run including the controller's death and
   the fallback re-route (packetReceived:count postrun-scalar check, same idiom as
   rsvpte_mbb.test/pcep_pcupd.test).
5. Standard undisposed-object postrun guard.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: PcepFallbackDiamond.ned

import inet.common.scenario.ScenarioManager;
import inet.node.mpls.RsvpMplsRouter;
import inet.node.inet.StandardHost;

//
// Ad hoc diamond, with real end-to-end hosts, identical to pcep_pcupd.test's own
// PcepPcupdDiamond, PLUS a fifth router (PceRouter) hanging off LSR4 on its own leaf link,
// running the ~Pce -- see this file's own %description for why it is deliberately NOT
// co-located with LSR4 itself.
//
network PcepFallbackDiamond
{
    parameters:
        **.ipv4.configurator.networkConfiguratorModule = "";
    submodules:
        host1: StandardHost {
            @display("p=50,200");
            gates: pppg[1];
        }
        host4: StandardHost {
            @display("p=650,200");
            gates: pppg[1];
        }
        LSR1: RsvpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=200,200");
            gates: pppg[3];
        }
        LSR2: RsvpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=400,100");
            gates: pppg[2];
        }
        LSR3: RsvpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=400,300");
            gates: pppg[2];
        }
        LSR4: RsvpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=600,200");
            gates: pppg[4];
        }
        PceRouter: RsvpMplsRouter {
            @display("p=600,350");
            gates: pppg[1];
        }
        scenarioManager: ScenarioManager {
            @display("p=100,100;is=s");
        }
    connections:
        host1.pppg[0] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 10Mbps; } <--> LSR1.pppg[0];
        LSR1.pppg[1] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 600kbps; } <--> LSR2.pppg[0];
        LSR2.pppg[1] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 600kbps; } <--> LSR4.pppg[0];
        LSR1.pppg[2] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 10Mbps; } <--> LSR3.pppg[0];
        LSR3.pppg[1] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 10Mbps; } <--> LSR4.pppg[1];
        LSR4.pppg[2] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 10Mbps; } <--> host4.pppg[0];
        LSR4.pppg[3] <--> { delay = 1ms; datarate = 10Mbps; } <--> PceRouter.pppg[0];
}

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Addressing (identical to pcep_pcupd.test's own PcepPcupdDiamond for host1/LSR1..4/host4),
%# PLUS the new LSR4<->PceRouter leaf link, deliberately given a LOWER address
%# (10.0.4.x) than LSR4's existing highest interface (10.0.5.1) so LSR4's own "auto" routerId
%# pick (the highest of its interface addresses) is unaffected by this test's added node:
%#   LSR4.ppp3=10.0.4.9 <-> PceRouter.ppp0=10.0.4.10
%#   LSR4 = max(10.0.2.2, 10.0.4.2, 10.0.5.1, 10.0.4.9) = 10.0.5.1 (unchanged)
%#   PceRouter = 10.0.4.10 (its only interface)
%# Every other router's routerId is exactly as in pcep_pcupd.test's own addressing note:
%#   LSR1 = 10.0.3.1, LSR2 = 10.0.2.1, LSR3 = 10.0.4.1.
%# The PCEP session connects LSR1's Pcc to PceRouter's routerId (10.0.4.10, genuinely
%# multi-hop, off the tunnel's own LSR2/LSR3 forwarding branches entirely).
%file: LSR1.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.0.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.1.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
name: ppp2	inet_addr: 10.0.3.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 5
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp2
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR2.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.1.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.2.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR3.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.3.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 5
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.4.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 5
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR4.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.2.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.4.2	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 5
name: ppp2	inet_addr: 10.0.5.1	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
name: ppp3	inet_addr: 10.0.4.9	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp1
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp2
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp3
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: PceRouter.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.4.10	MULTICAST	MTU: 1500	Groups: 224.0.0.0	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
224.0.0.0	*	255.0.0.0	H	0	ppp0
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: host1.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.0.1	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
10.0.0.2	*		255.255.255.255	H	0	ppp0
default:	10.0.0.2	0.0.0.0		G	0	ppp0
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: host4.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.5.2	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
10.0.5.1	*		255.255.255.255	H	0	ppp0
default:	10.0.5.1	0.0.0.0		G	0	ppp0
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# fecid 1 is statically bound to lspid 100 (tunnel 1's ORIGINAL Lsp_Id); the whole point of
%# this test is that the state-timeout-driven make-before-break cutover rebinds it to the
%# fresh, LOCALLY-computed replacement Lsp_Id (101) itself.
%file: LSR1_fec.xml
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<fectable>
	<fecentry>
		<id>1</id>
		<destination>10.0.5.2</destination>
		<tunnel_id>1</tunnel_id>
		<endpoint>LSR4%routerId</endpoint>
		<lspid>100</lspid>
	</fecentry>
</fectable>

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: LSR1_rsvp.xml
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<sessions>
	<session>
		<endpoint>LSR4%routerId</endpoint>
		<tunnel_id>1</tunnel_id>

		<paths>
			<path>
				<lspid>100</lspid>
				<bandwidth>50000</bandwidth>
				<permanent>true</permanent>
			</path>
		</paths>
	</session>
</sessions>

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# PceRouter (and only it) is killed at t=8s -- well after tunnel 1 is up and delegated -- and
%# never restarted: this test is specifically about a controller that never comes back.
%file: scenario.xml
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<scenario>
	<at t="8s">
		<shutdown module="PceRouter"/>
	</at>
</scenario>

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%inifile: test.ini

[General]
ned-path = .;../../../../src
network = PcepFallbackDiamond
sim-time-limit = 18s
total-stack = 64MiB
record-vector-results = false
cmdenv-express-mode = false
%# rsvp modules at detail (to capture the CSPF/label-install/reporting EV_DETAIL lines) and
%# the classifier + PCEP apps at info; everything else off -- same convention as
%# pcep_pcupd.test/rsvpte_mbb.test. Per-module cmdenv-log-level overrides are matched in FILE
%# ORDER (first matching pattern wins), so specific overrides MUST be declared before the
%# general catch-all below.
**.LSR1.rsvp.cmdenv-log-level = detail
**.LSR1.classifier.cmdenv-log-level = info
**.LSR1.app[0].cmdenv-log-level = info
**.PceRouter.app[0].cmdenv-log-level = info
**.scenarioManager.cmdenv-log-level = info
**.cmdenv-log-level = off

**.host1.numApps = 1
**.host1.app[0].typename = "UdpBasicApp"
**.host1.app[0].localPort = 100
**.host1.app[0].destPort = 100
**.host1.app[0].messageLength = 128 bytes
**.host1.app[0].sendInterval = 0.02s
**.host1.app[0].destAddresses = "10.0.5.2"

**.host4.numApps = 1
**.host4.app[0].typename = "UdpSink"
**.host4.app[0].localPort = 100

**.host1.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "host1.rt"
**.host4.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "host4.rt"
**.LSR1.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR1.rt"
**.LSR2.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR2.rt"
**.LSR3.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR3.rt"
**.LSR4.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "LSR4.rt"
**.PceRouter.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "PceRouter.rt"

**.LSR1.classifier.config = xmldoc("LSR1_fec.xml")
**.LSR1.rsvp.traffic = xmldoc("LSR1_rsvp.xml")

**.LSR1.rsvp.computeEro = true
**.LSR1.rsvp.computationMode = "pce"
**.LSR1.rsvp.pccModule = "^.app[0]"
**.LSR1.rsvp.delegate = true

**.LSR*.rsvp.helloInterval = 0.2s
**.LSR*.rsvp.helloTimeout = 0.5s
**.PceRouter.rsvp.helloInterval = 0.2s
**.PceRouter.rsvp.helloTimeout = 0.5s

%# PCEP: LSR1 (ingress) runs the Pcc, PceRouter runs the Pce, wired to PceRouter's own (fully
%# converged) Ted -- see this file's %description for why the Pce is NOT co-located with LSR4.
**.LSR1.hasTcp = true
**.LSR1.numApps = 1
**.LSR1.app[0].typename = "Pcc"
**.LSR1.app[0].pceAddress = "10.0.4.10"
**.LSR1.app[0].localAddress = "10.0.3.1"
**.LSR1.app[0].rsvpteModule = "^.rsvp"
**.LSR1.app[0].keepaliveTime = 2s
**.LSR1.app[0].deadTimer = 10s
**.LSR1.app[0].reconnectInterval = 1s
**.LSR1.app[0].stateTimeout = 5s

**.PceRouter.hasTcp = true
**.PceRouter.numApps = 1
**.PceRouter.app[0].typename = "Pce"
**.PceRouter.app[0].tedModule = "^.ted"
**.PceRouter.app[0].keepaliveTime = 2s
**.PceRouter.app[0].deadTimer = 10s

**.ppp[*].queue.typename = "DropTailQueue"
**.ppp[*].queue.packetCapacity = 10

*.*.hasStatus = true
**.scenarioManager.script = xmldoc("scenario.xml")

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Assertion 1: PCEP session up, tunnel 1 established, and delegated (PCRpt) -- all before
%# PceRouter is shut down (ordering regex; %contains-regex matches with re.DOTALL, so a lone
%# ".*" filler line can absorb any number of intervening lines, same convention as
%# pcep_pcreq.test/pcep_pcupd.test's own ordering regexes).
%contains-regex: stdout
PCEP session with .* is now OPERATIONAL
.*
reporting delegated LSP UP to PCE \(plspId=1, lspid=100, .*\)
.*
processing <shutdown> command\.\.\.
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Assertion 2: the state timeout is armed on session loss (not an immediate fallback) --
%# and, separately (further down in the log, only after its own 5s delay actually elapses),
%# it expires and tells RsvpTe to fall back for PLSP-ID 1.
%contains: stdout
PCEP session lost with 1 delegated LSP(s) outstanding; starting state timeout (5)
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%contains: stdout
PCEP state timeout (5) expired with the session still down; 1 delegated LSP(s) falling back to local path computation
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Assertion 3: the fallback re-route (a fresh replacement lspid, 101) is computed via LOCAL
%# CSPF, not via any further PCEP exchange.
%contains: stdout
PCEP controller state timeout expired for delegated PLSP-ID 1 (lspid=100): falling back to LOCAL path computation (C6 CSPF)
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%contains-regex: stdout
CSPF computed ERO for session \(dest=10.0.5.1, lspid=101\): .*
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%not-contains: stdout
PCE computed ERO for session (dest=10.0.5.1, lspid=101)
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Assertion 4: the cutover completes (classifier rebound from lspid 100 to 101) and traffic
%# keeps flowing end to end, strongly, across the whole run -- same postrun-scalar idiom as
%# pcep_pcupd.test/rsvpte_mbb.test.
%contains-regex: stdout
make-before-break cutover: lspid=101 is up, switching traffic away from lspid=100.*
make-before-break cutover: rebinding fec id 1 from lspid 100 to lspid 101.*
sending PathTear to .*
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%postrun-command: grep "packetReceived:count" results/General-#0.sca | awk '$NF > 650 { print "DELIVERED", $0 }' > delivered.out
%contains: delivered.out
DELIVERED
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%postrun-command: grep "undisposed object:" test.out > test_undisposed.out || true
%not-contains: test_undisposed.out
undisposed object: (
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
